post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_42192396_42192415_0": {"length": 21, "quality": 0.9545454545454546, "section_id": 6138}}, "n3337": {"so_42192396_42192415_0": {"length": 21, "quality": 0.9545454545454546, "section_id": 5902}}, "n4659": {"so_42192396_42192415_0": {"length": 21, "quality": 0.9545454545454546, "section_id": 7635}}}, "42192415": {"Id": "42192415", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Subtraction operation can be performed on two address data type but not addition.<br>\nFor addition, either both operand of <code>+</code> shall be of arithmetic type or one operand shall be a pointer and other shall be an integer type.  </br></p>\n<h3>C++11-\u00a7 5.7/1:</h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_42192396_42192415_0\">For addition, either both operands shall have arithmetic or unscoped enumeration type, or one operand shall be a pointer to a completely-defined object type and the other shall have integral or unscoped enumeration type.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "2455888", "LastActivityDate": "2017-02-12T19:54:03.330", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2017-02-12T19:48:17.677", "ParentId": "42192396", "CommentCount": "7", "LastEditDate": "2017-02-12T19:54:03.330", "OwnerUserId": "2455888"}, "42192396": {"ViewCount": "49", "Body": "<p>how this convertion done from unsigned char* to unsigned short?</p>\n<pre><code>#include&lt;iostream&gt;\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main()\n{\n    unsigned short x;\n    x= (unsigned char*)&amp;x - (unsigned char*) 0x8888;\n    cout&lt;&lt;us&lt;&lt;endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>when I am trying to add like this </p>\n<pre><code>x= (unsigned char*)&amp;x + (unsigned char*) 0x8888;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then error comes up. it says \"invalid operands of types 'unsigned char*' and 'unsigned char*' to binary 'operator+' \" please help me to understand this syntax.</p>\n", "Title": "how this convertion done in c++ from unsigned char* to unsigned short? x= (unsigned char*)&x - (unsigned char*) 0x8888;", "CreationDate": "2017-02-12T19:46:34.217", "LastActivityDate": "2017-02-13T09:03:07.640", "CommentCount": "2", "LastEditDate": "2017-02-12T19:47:08.613", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "2100815", "Id": "42192396", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "5488179", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "42200207": {"Id": "42200207", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>You could convert pointer to <code>int/short/long</code> using <code>cstdint C++11</code> as below, But I'm not certain whether it is advisable to add pointers as mentioned by <code>@haccks</code></p>\n<pre><code>#include&lt;iostream&gt;\n#include &lt;cstdint&gt;\n\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main()\n{\n    unsigned short x;\n    //x= (unsigned char*)&amp;x + (unsigned char*) 0x8888;\n    x = static_cast&lt;unsigned short&gt;(reinterpret_cast&lt;uintptr_t&gt;(&amp;x)) + static_cast&lt;unsigned short&gt;(0x8888);\n    cout&lt;&lt;x&lt;&lt;endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Refer to this <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/21574449/why-is-cast-from-x-to-y-loses-precision-a-hard-error-and-what-is-suitable\">link</a> for more information.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2017-02-13T09:03:07.640", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2017-02-13T09:03:07.640", "ParentId": "42192396", "CommentCount": "0", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T11:53:17.443", "OwnerUserId": "4380130"}});